Rating: 4
One of our new favorite soups. We'd never had green pozole before, but have tried many versions around Austin and found this to be the tastiest yet. We wanted a large batch for extra leftovers, so we used 12 cups broth (in place of water). We wound up wasting about a cup of the broth, so next time will go with 10 or 11 and use water for cooking the tomatillo/onion mixture. Substitutions: Canned chicken broth for water, 3 lb. chicken breast instead of thighs. Additions: 1/2 onion, 1 extra clove garlic, 1/4 extra pepitos (pumpkin seeds), 1/4 extra lb. tomatillos, 1 more jalapeno, 1/4 cup extra cilantro, 30 oz. add'l hominy. In addition to the avocado in lime juice (very tasty), we recommend making a small batch of pico de gallo (tomatoes, onion, jalapeno, cilantro, lime juice, splash of red wine vinegar, shake of habanero hot sauce) and serving it as an accompaniment (spoon these into the soup). With the pico and lime-avocado, you may not want extra lime juice, so taste first. Even in our very Tex-Mex grocery store, we could not find raw pepitos. We had to stop by our local health-food store which had them in the bulk section, but it was worth the extra stop. Lastly, we found the amount of chicken to be satisfactory with the extra broth, but agree that this recipe would be too meaty w/o adding broth. Even with our large batch, we could've reduced the chicken by 1/2 pound easily.

